<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,546,1075]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<materialsCitation ID-GBIF-Occurrence="1915273573" country="Canada" location="Oklahoma" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" specimenCount="1" stateProvince="Oklahoma">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,978,1003]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Comments.</emphasis>
While our female adults are consistent with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Walker" baseAuthorityYear="1853" box="[857,1135,978,1003]" class="Insecta" family="Agromyzidae" genus="Aulagromyza" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="populicola">
<emphasis box="[857,1135,978,1003]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Aulagromyza populicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, it would be desirable for male specimens to be obtained from the 
<collectingRegion box="[600,717,1014,1039]" country="United States of America" name="Oklahoma" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Oklahoma</collectingRegion>
population to confirm that it is conspecific with those in 
<collectingCountry box="[1352,1436,1014,1039]" name="Canada" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Canada</collectingCountry>
and Europe, due to the differences in mine characteristics and pupation site noted above.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
